{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"tool_UW2IffZDXLeIMXCo1VLPwNpq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Implementation Plan — TST-001: FS-RBAC-03 Live RBAC Enforcement\n     2→\n     3→**Status:** READY\n     4→**Ticket:** TST-001\n     5→**Updated:** 2026-03-18\n     6→**Research Status:** warn (see research findings for PRD overrides)\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## Executive Summary\n    11→\n    12→This plan implements live RBAC enforcement for all mutation APIs (POST/PUT/DELETE) with audit logging and frontend role synchronization. Based on research findings, we adapt the PRD assumptions to the actual codebase:\n    13→\n    14→| PRD Assumption | Research Finding | Adaptation |\n    15→|----------------|------------------|------------|\n    16→| JWT claims auth | X-Profile-Key header auth | Custom WebFlux filter with header parsing |\n    17→| Redux state | Zustand with persistence | Extend Zustand store with SSE listener |\n    18→| WebSocket push | SSE already exists for flows | Extend SSE for role notifications |\n    19→| Spring Security | Not in classpath | Custom WebFlux filters (no Spring Security) |\n    20→\n    21→---\n    22→\n    23→## AIDD:DECISIONS\n    24→\n    25→### Architecture Decisions\n    26→\n    27→1. **No Spring Security** — Adding spring-boot-starter-security introduces significant complexity and potential conflicts with existing WebFlux setup. Instead, implement custom `WebFilter` for RBAC.\n    28→\n    29→2. **Extend SSE instead of WebSocket** — SSE infrastructure already exists (`subscribeToFlowEvents` in apiClient.ts). Adding WebSocket requires new dependencies and infrastructure. SSE is sufficient for unidirectional server-to-client role updates.\n    30→\n    31→3. **Role Caching with Caffeine** — Backend uses Caffeine cache (already in classpath). Cache profile roles with 5-minute TTL to meet P95 ≤ 10ms latency requirement.\n    32→\n    33→4. **Audit Log as Separate Table** — Follow existing pattern (note_entry table) with PostgreSQL JSONB for flexible metadata.\n    34→\n    35→5. **Header-Based Identity** — Use `X-Profile-Key` (format: `namespace:reference`) and `X-Profile-Auth` headers for identity extraction.\n    36→\n    37→---\n    38→\n    39→## AIDD:NON_NEGOTIABLES\n    40→\n    41→- All POST/PUT/DELETE APIs must return 403 for unauthorized requests\n    42→- Audit log must capture: timestamp, actor profile key, action (GRANT/REVOKE/DENIED), target resource, result\n    43→- Frontend role guards must update within 5 seconds of backend role change\n    44→- RBAC check latency P95 ≤ 10ms\n    45→- Zero breaking changes to existing API contracts\n    46→\n    47→---\n    48→\n    49→## AIDD:RISKS\n    50→\n    51→| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |\n    52→|------|--------|------------|\n    53→| RBAC filter performance | High | Caffeine cache with 5min TTL; async audit logging |\n    54→| Cache stale roles | Medium | Cache invalidation on role change via SSE broadcast |\n    55→| SSE connection drops | Low | Auto-reconnect with exponential backoff in frontend |\n    56→| Missing audit logs | Medium | Async logging with error queue; never block request |\n    57→| Profile service unavailable | High | Circuit breaker pattern; fail-closed (deny access) |\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## Milestones & Iterations\n    62→\n    63→### Phase 1: Backend Foundation (Days 1-3)\n    64→**Goal:** Core RBAC filter and audit infrastructure\n    65→\n    66→#### 1.1 Database Migration\n    67→**File:** `backend-mcp/src/main/resources/db/changelog/rbac/db.changelog-rbac-001.yaml`\n    68→\n    69→```yaml\n    70→# Create audit_log table\n    71→- changeSet:\n    72→    id: rbac-0001-audit-log\n    73→    author: ai-advent\n    74→    context: rbac\n    75→    changes:\n    76→      - createTable:\n    77→          tableName: rbac_audit_log\n    78→          columns:\n    79→            - column:\n    80→                name: id\n    81→                type: UUID\n    82→                defaultValueComputed: gen_random_uuid()\n    83→                constraints:\n    84→                  primaryKey: true\n    85→            - column:\n    86→                name: timestamp\n    87→                type: TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE\n    88→                defaultValueComputed: now()\n    89→                constraints:\n    90→                  nullable: false\n    91→            - column:\n    92→                name: actor_namespace\n    93→                type: VARCHAR(32)\n    94→                constraints:\n    95→                  nullable: false\n    96→            - column:\n    97→                name: actor_reference\n    98→                type: VARCHAR(128)\n    99→                constraints:\n   100→                  nullable: false\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"tool_qWaqYNlqBZaQ20pUy0Eo4Z7p","session_id":"e8271fef-d7fa-47ae-9a86-a79be1e8c480","uuid":"a557c087-9262-452c-bf9c-c6a893b03110"}
